       445 Soda Hall<br>
       Office hours: Thu 1:00-2:00
</UL>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<H2>Course Grading</H2>

<UL>
  <LI>50% Classroom Discussion
  <LI>50% <a href="Assignments/index.html">Homeworks and Mini-Projects</a>
  <li> Pass/No Pass: "Pass" is C+ or better.
</UL>
</td></tr>
</table>

<H2><a href="Student_Pics/students.html">Class Photos</a></H2>

<H2>Course Time and Place</H2>

<P><b>In real life:</b> Thursdays, 3:30-5:00 PM, 405 Soda Hall</P>

<table border="0">
<tr><td valign="top"><b>On the Web:</b> </td>
<td valign="top">This constantly-evolving home page can be found at:<br>
<TT>http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~gribble/cs39c</TT></td></tr>
</table>

<H2>Course Readings</H2>

<P>Notes and readings will be placed on the Web (of course!).  There
will be several pages of background readings assigned each week.  The
readings will either be handed out or listed on the Web page
corresponding to that week's topic.  You are responsible for reading the
material, <b>and</b> writing 1-2 paragraphs per reading giving your
impressions and thoughts.  The summaries should be informal and brief,
and should consist of <i>your reactions</i> to the readings, <i>not</i>
a rehash of the content.<p>  You should <i>email</i> your summaries to
<a
href="mailto:randy@@cs.berkeley.edu">Prof. Randy Katz
</a>.  (You will have email working by the second class meeting.)<p>


Supplementary reading goodies:

<ul>
  <li> An <A HREF="Bibliography.html">annotated bibliography</A>
       of suggested additional books and articles.  (Mostly real print
       stuff, not on the Internet)
  <li> A collection of <a href="Links.html">useful links</a> related to
       the social and technological history of computing and communications.
</ul>

<H2>Course Outline</H2>

<P>The course will cover four main topic areas:</P>

<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="Comm/index.html">History of Communications Infrastructures</A>,
  <LI><A HREF="Comp/index.html">History of Computing</A>,
  <LI><A HREF="Societal/societal_index.html">Societal Impact of Computing
  and Communication</A>,
  <LI>Mobile Computing: The Convergence of Computing and Communication <B>(still
  under construction)</B>.
</UL>

<H3>Discussion Topic Sequence</H3>

<P>The topic areas are divided into 24 &quot;mini-topics&quot;. We'll cover
two &quot;mini-topics&quot; during each 90 minute class meeting. You'll
prepare for each meeting by reading the background material, and during
class we'll spend about 15-20 minutes highlighting key points from the reading,
followed by 20-25 minutes of discussion. <BR>
<BR>
